  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0007",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1996_Solutions_1996s_page_003",
    "primary_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1996_Solutions_1996s_page_003_10",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 2,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1996_Solutions_1996s_page_003_10",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Since sinA and sin B are conjugate, their eigenvalues must be the same, and so we must have sinx = 1. This implies cosx = 0, so that sin B is the identity matrix, as must be sinA, a contradiction. Thus A cannot exist.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5568627450980392,
          0.3715151515151515,
          0.9192156862745098,
          0.4296969696969697
        ],
        "order": 8
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1996_Solutions_1996s_page_003_11",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Alternate solution (due to Craig Helfgott and Alex Popa): Define both sinA and cosA by the usual power series. Since A commutes with itself, the power series identity",
        "bbox": [
          0.556078431372549,
          0.43454545454545457,
          0.9192156862745098,
          0.49272727272727274
        ],
        "order": 9
      }
    ]
  },
  {
