        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1996_Solutions_1996s_page_003_4",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Now relabel the numbers so they appear in order as fol- lows:",
        "bbox": [
          0.12705882352941175,
          0.45454545454545453,
          0.4894117647058824,
          0.4824242424242424
        ],
        "order": 10
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1996_Solutions_1996s_page_003_5",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "where without loss of generality we assume an−1 > an−2. By considering the pairs an−2, an and an−1, an−3 and using the trivial fact an > an−1, we deduce an−2 > an−3. We then compare the pairs an–4, an−2 and an−1, an−3, and using that an−1 > an−2, we deduce an−3 > an−4. Continuing in this fashion, we prove that an > an−1 > . . · > a1 and so ak = k for k = 1, 2, . .,n, i.e. that the optimal arrangement is as claimed. In par- ticular, the maximum value of the sum is",
        "bbox": [
          0.12627450980392158,
          0.5218181818181818,
          0.49019607843137253,
          0.6539393939393939
        ],
        "order": 11
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0009",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1996_Solutions_1996s_page_003",
